A051001.name: Sum of 4th powers of odd divisors of n.
formula: Multiplicative with a(2^e) = 1 and a(p^e) = (p^(4*e+4)-1)/(p^4-1) for p > 2. - _Amiram Eldar_, Sep 14 2020

A051002.name: Sum of 5th powers of odd divisors of n.
formula: The preceding g.f. is also 34*sigma_5(x^2) - 64*sigma_5(x^4) - sigma_5(-x), with sigma_5 the g.f. of A001160. Compare this with the Apostol reference which gives the g.f. of a(n)*(-1)^(n+1). - _Wolfdieter Lang_, Jan 31 2017
Multiplicative with a(2^e) = 1 and a(p^e) = (p^(5*e+5)-1)/(p^5-1) for p > 2. - _Amiram Eldar_, Sep 14 2020
Sum_{k=1..n} a(k) ~ Pi^6 * n^6 / 11340. - _Vaclav Kotesovec_, Sep 24 2020

A051003.name: Beastly (or hateful) numbers: numbers containing the string 666 in their decimal expansion.

A051004.name: Numbers divisible both by their individual digits and by the sum of their digits.

A051005.name: PartitionsQ[ A035359 ], i.e., prime values of PartitionsQ.

A051006.name: Prime constant: decimal value of (A010051 interpreted as a binary number).
formula: Prime constant C = Sum_{k>=1} 1/2^p(k), where p(k) is the k-th prime. - _Alexander Adamchuk_, Aug 22 2006
Equals Sum_{k>=1} pi(k)/2^(k+1), where pi(k) = A000720(k). (End)

A051007.name: Continued fraction for prime constant A051006.

A051009.name: Reduced denominators of Newton's iteration for sqrt(2).
formula: For n>1, a(n) = 2*a(n-1)*sqrt(2*a(n-1)^2+1). - Mario Catalani (mario.catalani(AT)unito.it), May 27 2003
For n>0: a(n) = Sum_{r=0..2^(n-1)-1} binomial(2^n, 2*r+1)*2^r. - Mario Catalani (mario.catalani(AT)unito.it), May 30 2003
For n>0, a(n) = sqrt((A001601(n)^2-1)/2). - _Jose Hortal_, Apr 14 2012
a(1)=1, a(2)=2, a(n) = 2 * a(n-1) * cos(2^(n-3) * arccos(3)). - _Daniel Suteu_, Dec 01 2016

A051010.name: Triangle T(m,n) giving of number of steps in the Euclidean algorithm for gcd(m,n) with 0<=m<n.

A051011.name: Numerator of average of number of steps in Euclidean algorithm for all gcd(m,n) with 0<=m<n.

A051012.name: Denominator of average of number of steps in Euclidean algorithm for all gcd(m,n) with 0 <= m < n.

A051016.name: Numbers n for which r^n-floor(r^n) < 1/2, where r is the real root of x^3-x-1.

A051017.name: Numbers n for which r^n-floor(r^n) > 1/2, where r is the real root of x^3-x-1.

A051021.name: Decimal expansion of Mills's constant, assuming the Riemann Hypothesis is true.

A051022.name: Interpolate 0's between each pair of digits of n.
formula: a(n) = n if n < 10, otherwise a(floor(n/10))*100 + n mod 10. - _Reinhard Zumkeller_, Apr 20 2011 [Corrected by _Kevin Ryde_, Nov 07 2020]
a(n) = A338754(n)/11. - _Kritsada Moomuang_, Oct 20 2019 [Corrected by _Kevin Ryde_, Nov 07 2020]

A051023.name: Middle column of rule-30 1-D cellular automaton, from a lone 1 cell.
formula: For n>= 2, a(n) = (A328100(n) OR A328101(n)) XOR A328101(1+n). ["Sideways evaluation"]

A051024.name: Values of n for which pi_{4,3}(p_n) - pi_{4,1}(p_n) = -1, where p_n is the n-th prime and pi_{m,a}(x) is the number of primes <= x which are congruent to a (mod m).

A051025.name: Primes p for which pi_{4,3}(p) - pi_{4,1}(p) = -1, where pi_{m,a}(x) is the number of primes <= x which are congruent to a (mod m).

A051026.name: Number of primitive subsequences of {1, 2, ..., n}.

A051027.name: a(n) = sigma(sigma(n)) = sum of the divisors of the sum of the divisors of n.
formula: a(p) = sigma(p+1) = A000203(p+1), for p prime. - _Wesley Ivan Hurt_, Feb 14 2014
a(n) = 2*n iff n = 2^q with M_(q+1) = 2^(q+1) - 1 is a Mersenne prime, hence iff n = 2^q with q in A090748. - _Bernard Schott_, Aug 08 2019
a(n) >= 2*n for even n, with equality only when n = 2^k and 2^(k+1) - 1 is prime (Sándor, 1989). - _Amiram Eldar_, Mar 09 2021

A051031.name: Triangle read by rows: T(n,r) is the number of not necessarily connected r-regular graphs with n nodes, 0 <= r < n.

A051032.name: Summatory Rudin-Shapiro sequence for 2^(n-1).
formula: Apart from leading term, just A000051 (2^n + 1) doubled up.

A051034.name: Minimal number of primes needed to sum to n.
formula: a(n) = 1 iff n is prime. a(2n) = 2 (for n > 1) if Goldbachs's conjecture is true. a(2n+1) = 2 (for n >= 1) if 2n+1 is not prime, but 2n-1 is. a(2n+1) >= 3 (for n >= 1) if both 2n+1 and 2n-1 are not primes (for sufficiently large n, a(2n+1) = 3 by Vinogradov's theorem, 1937). - _Franz Vrabec_, Nov 30 2004
a(n) <= 3 for all n, assuming the Goldbach conjecture. - _N. J. A. Sloane_, Jan 20 2007
a(2n+1) <= 5, see Tao 2012. - _Charles R Greathouse IV_, Jul 09 2012

A051035.name: Composite numbers which can be represented as the sum of two primes (i.e., A002808 excluding A025583).

A051037.name: 5-smooth numbers, i.e., numbers whose prime divisors are all <= 5.
formula: Let s(n) = Card(k | a(k)<n) and f(n) = log(n*sqrt(30))^3/(6*log(2)*log(3)*log(5)). Then s(n) = f(n) + O(log(n)). Conjecture: s(n)=f(n) + O(log log n). For example, s(10000000) = 768 is well approximated by f(10000000) = 769, 3... (see graphic given as link). - _Benoit Cloitre_, Dec 30 2001
The characteristic function of this sequence is given by:
Sum_{n>=1} x^a(n) = Sum_{n>=1}-Möbius(30*n)*x^n/(1-x^n). - _Paul D. Hanna_, Sep 18 2011
Sum_{n>=1} 1/a(n) = Product_{primes p <= 5} p/(p-1) = (2*3*5)/(1*2*4) = 15/4. - _Amiram Eldar_, Sep 22 2020

A051038.name: 11-smooth numbers: numbers whose prime divisors are all <= 11.

A051040.name: 5-Stohr sequence.
formula: Terms are 2^(n-1) up to a(6) and then 31n-154.

A051041.name: Number of squarefree quaternary words of length n.
formula: Let L be the limit lim a(n)^{1/n}, which exists because a(n) is a submultiplicative sequence. Then L=2.6215080... (Shur 2010). See (Shur 2012) for the methods of estimating such limits. - _Arseny Shur_, Apr 26 2015

A051042.name: Number of ternary cubefree words of length n.
formula: Let L = lim a(n)^(1/n); then L exists since a(n) is submultiplicative. 2.7015614 < L < 2.7015616 (Shur 2012); the gap between the bounds can be made less than any given constant. - _Arseny Shur_, Apr 27 2015

A051043.name: Number of quaternary cubefree words of length n.

A051044.name: Odd values of the PartitionsQ function A000009.

A051045.name: Number of distinct resistances possible for n resistors with resistances 1, 2, ..., n, each connected in series or parallel to the previous one.

A051046.name: n for which pi(n) > n/(H_n-3/2), where pi is the prime-counting function and H_n is the n-th harmonic number.

A051049.name: Number of moves needed to solve an (n+1)-ring baguenaudier if two simultaneous moves of the two end rings are counted as one.
formula: a(n) = Sum_{k=0..n} Sum_{j=0..n-k, (j-k) mod 2 = 0} binomial(n-k, j). - _Paul Barry_, Jan 25 2005
Row sums of triangle A135221. - _Gary W. Adamson_, Nov 23 2007
a(n) = 2*a(n-1) + a(n-2) - 2*a(n-3), a(0) = a(1) = 1, a(2) = 4. Observed by G. Detlefs. See the W. Lang link. - _Wolfdieter Lang_, Oct 18 2010
a(n+2) = A001969(2^n+1) + A000069(2^n); evil + odious. - _Johannes W. Meijer_, Jun 24 2011, Jun 26 2011
a(n) = Sum_{k=0..n} Sum_{i=0..n} C(k-1,i). - _Wesley Ivan Hurt_, Sep 21 2017

A051050.name: Numerator of the probability that the convex hull of n+2 randomly chosen points in the unit ball B^n has n+1 vertices.

A051051.name: Denominators of the probability that the convex hull of n+2 randomly chosen points in the unit ball B^n has n+1 vertices (with factor of Pi^n dropped for n even).

A051054.name: a(n) = Sum_{k=1..n} C(n, floor(n/k)).
formula: a(n) is asymptotic to 2^n/sqrt(n*Pi/2). - _Benoit Cloitre_, Jan 11 2003

A051055.name: 'Connected' alternating sign n X n matrices, i.e., not made from smaller blocks.
formula: Sum_{k>=0} a(k)z^k/k!^2 = log(Sum_{k>=0} r(k)z^k/k!^2) where r(k) is the k-th Robbins number A005130(n).
a(n) = r(n) - (1/n)*Sum_{k=0..n-1} k*binomial(n, k)^2*r(n-k)*a(k), n > 0, a(0)=0, where r(k) is the k-th Robbins number A005130(n). - _Vladeta Jovovic_, Mar 16 2000

A051062.name: a(n) = 16*n + 8.
formula: a(n) = A118413(n+1,4) for n>3. - _Reinhard Zumkeller_, Apr 27 2006
a(n) = 32*n - a(n-1) for n>0, a(0)=8. - _Vincenzo Librandi_, Aug 06 2010

A051063.name: 27*n+9 or 27*n+18.
formula: a(n)=27*n-a(n-1) for n>0, a(0)=9. [_Vincenzo Librandi_, Aug 06 2010]

A051064.name: 3^a(n) exactly divides 3n. Or, 3-adic valuation of 3n.
formula: Multiplicative with a(p^e) = e+1 if p = 3; 1 if p <> 3. - _Vladeta Jovovic_, Aug 24 2002
Fixed point of the morphism: 1 -> 112; 2 -> 113; 3 -> 114; 4 -> 115; ...; starting from a(1) = 1. a(3n+1) = a(3n+2) = 1; a(3n) = 1 + a(n). - _Philippe Deléham_, Mar 29 2004
a(n) = (-1)*sum_{d divides n} mu(3d)*tau(n/d). - _Benoit Cloitre_, Jun 21 2007
Dirichlet g.f. zeta(s)/(1-1/3^s). - _R. J. Mathar_, Jun 13 2011
a(2n) = a(n), a(2n-1) = A254046(n). - _Cyril Damamme_, Aug 04 2015
G.f. A(x) satisfies: A(x) = A(x^3) + x/(1 - x). - _Ilya Gutkovskiy_, May 03 2019
Asymptotic mean: lim_{m->oo} (1/m) * Sum_{k=1..m} a(k) = 3/4. - _Amiram Eldar_, Sep 11 2020
a(n) = tau(n)/(tau(3*n) - tau(n)), where tau(n) = A000005(n). - _Peter Bala_, Jan 06 2021

A051065.name: a(n) = A004128(n) mod 2.
formula: a(0)=0, a(n) = (n + a(floor(n/3))) mod 2. - _Alex Ratushnyak_, Aug 17 2012

A051070.name: a(n) is the n-th term in sequence A_n, respecting the offset, or a(n) = -1 if A_n has fewer than n terms.

A051071.name: Primes p such that x^4 = -2 has a solution mod p.

A051072.name: Primes p such that x^6 = -2 has a solution mod p.

A051073.name: Primes p such that x^8 = -2 has a solution mod p.

A051090.name: Primes p such that x^42 = -2 has a solution mod p.

A051091.name: Primes p such that x^44 = -2 has a solution mod p.

A051092.name: Primes p such that x^46 = -2 has a solution mod p.

A051093.name: Primes p such that x^48 = -2 has a solution mod p.

A051099.name: Primes p such that x^60 = -2 has a solution mod p.

A051100.name: Primes p such that x^62 = -2 has a solution mod p.

A051101.name: Primes p such that x^64 = -2 has a solution mod p.

A051103.name: Numerator of a certain Selberg integral.

A051104.name: Denominator of a certain Selberg integral.

A051106.name: Second diagonal of triangle A048601.
formula: a(n) ~ Pi^(1/3) * exp(1/36) * 3^(3*n^2/2 - 3*n + 47/36) * n^(31/36) / (A^(1/3) * Gamma(1/3)^(2/3) * 2^(2*n^2 - 4*n + 31/12)), where A is the Glaisher-Kinkelin constant A074962. - _Vaclav Kotesovec_, Oct 26 2017

A051107.name: Numbers described with a single word in British English.

A051108.name: Numbers described with a single word in American English.

A051109.name: Hyperinflation sequence for banknotes.
formula: a(n) = 10*a(n-3) with n>2, a(0)=1, a(1)=2, a(2)=5. - _Philippe Deléham_, Apr 08 2013

A051111.name: Expansion of x/(x^4-3*x^3+4*x^2-2*x+1).
formula: a(5*n + 1) = F(5*n + 1), a(5*n + 2) = F(5*n + 3), a(5*n + 3) = 0, a(5*n - 1) = a(5*n) = -F(5*n), where F = A000045 the Fibonacci sequence.

A051112.name: Number of monotone Boolean functions of n variables with 4 mincuts. Also Sperner systems with 4 blocks.

A051113.name: Number of monotone Boolean functions of n variables with 5 mincuts.

A051114.name: Number of monotone Boolean functions of n variables with 6 mincuts.

A051115.name: Number of monotone Boolean functions of n variables with 7 mincuts.

A051116.name: Number of monotone Boolean functions of n variables with 8 mincuts.

A051117.name: Number of monotone Boolean functions of n variables with 9 mincuts.

A051118.name: Number of monotone Boolean functions of n variables with 10 mincuts.

A051119.name: n/p^k, where p = largest prime dividing n and p^k = highest power of p dividing n.

A051120.name: Start with 1; at n-th step, write down what is in the sequence so far.

A051121.name: Dates at fortnightly intervals starting on Jan 01 of a leap year in the Julian calendar.

A051125.name: Table T(n,k) = max{n,k} read by antidiagonals (n >= 1, k >= 1).

A051126.name: Table T(n,k) = n mod k read by antidiagonals (n >= 1, k >= 1).
formula: As a linear array, the sequence is a(n) = A002260(n) mod A004736 (n) or a(n) = (n-(t*(t+1)/2)) mod ((t*t+3*t+4)/2-n), where t = floor((-1+sqrt(8*n-7))/2). - _Boris Putievskiy_, Dec 19 2012

A051127.name: Table T(n,k) = k mod n read by antidiagonals (n >= 1, k >= 1).
formula: As a linear array, the sequence is a(n) = A004736(n) mod A002260(n) or a(n) = ((t*t+3*t+4)/2-n) mod (n-(t*(t+1)/2)), where t = floor((-1+sqrt(8*n-7))/2). - _Boris Putievskiy_, Dec 17 2012

A051128.name: Table T(n,k) = n^k read by upwards antidiagonals (n >= 1, k >= 1).

A051129.name: Table T(n,k) = k^n read by upwards antidiagonals (n >= 1, k >= 1).
formula: a(n) = (n - b(n) * (b(n) - 1) / 2)^(b(n) * (b(n) + 1) / 2 - n + 1), where b(n) = [ 1/2 + sqrt(2 * n) ]. (b(n) is the n-th term of A002024.) - Robert A. Stump (bee_ess107(AT)yahoo.com), Aug 29 2002

A051130.name: Indices of prime Bell numbers A000110.

A051132.name: Number of ordered pairs of integers (x,y) with x^2+y^2 < n^2.

A051135.name: a(n) = number of times n appears in the Hofstadter-Conway $10000 sequence A004001.
formula: a(n) = A188163(n+1) - A188163(n). [after _Reinhard Zumkeller_'s Jun 03 2011 comment above]
a(n) = 1 if and only if A093879(n-1) = 1. [See A188163 for a reason.]

A051136.name: Number of 2-colored generalized Frobenius partitions.
formula: Expansion of phi(q) / f(-q)^2 in powers of q where phi(), f() are Ramanujan theta functions.
Expansion of q^(1/12) * eta(q^2)^5 / (eta(q)^4 * eta(q^4)^2) in powers of q. - _Michael Somos_, Apr 25 2003
Euler transform of period 4 sequence [4, -1, 4, 1, ...]. - _Michael Somos_, Apr 25 2003
G.f. is a period 1 Fourier series which satisfies f(-1 / (144 t)) = 24^(-1/2) (t/i)^(-1/2) g(t) where q = exp(2 Pi i t) and g(t) is g.f. for A137828.
G.f.: Product_{k>0} (1 + x^k)^3 / ((1 - x^k) * (1 + x^(2*k))^2). - _Michael Somos_, Feb 12 2008

A051137.name: Table T(n,k) read by antidiagonals: number of necklaces allowing turnovers (bracelets) with n beads of k colors.
formula: T(n, k) = (k^floor((n+1)/2) + k^ceiling((n+1)/2)) / 4 + (1/(2*n)) * Sum_{d divides n} phi(d) * k^(n/d). - _Robert A. Russell_, Sep 21 2018
G.f. for column k: (kx/4)*(kx+x+2)/(1-kx^2) - Sum_{d>0} phi(d)*log(1-kx^d)/2d. - _Robert A. Russell_, Sep 28 2018
T(n, k) = (k^floor((n+1)/2) + k^ceiling((n+1)/2))/4 + (1/(2*n))*Sum_{i=1..n} k^gcd(n,i). (See A075195 formulas.) - _Richard L. Ollerton_, May 04 2021

A051138.name: Divisibility sequence associated with elliptic curve y^2 + y = x^3 - x and point (1, 0).
formula: 0 = a(n)*a(n+4) - a(n+1)*a(n+3) - a(n+2)*a(n+2) for all n in Z. - _Michael Somos_, Jul 07 2014
0 = a(n)*a(n+5) + a(n+1)*a(n+4) - 5*a(n+2)*a(n+3) for all n in Z. - _Michael Somos_, Jul 07 2014

A051139.name: A000994-A000995.
formula: For recurrence see A000994 and A000995.

A051141.name: Triangle read by rows: a(n, m) = S1(n, m)*3^(n-m), where S1 are the signed Stirling numbers of first kind A008275 (n >= 1, 1 <= m <= n).
formula: E.g.f. for the m-th column of the signed triangle: (log(1 + 3*x)/3)^m/m!.

A051142.name: Generalized Stirling number triangle of first kind.
formula: E.g.f. for the m-th column of the signed triangle: (log(1 + 4*x)/4)^m/m!.
a(n, m) = S1(n, m)*4^(n-m), with S1(n, m) := A008275(n, m) (signed Stirling1 triangle).

A051143.name: Numbers n such that n-th prime is a partition number.

A051144.name: Nonsquarefree nonsquares: each entry has a square factor but is not a perfect square itself.

A051145.name: a(0)=0, a(1)=1, a(n) = smallest number such that sequence b(n) = a(n) OR a(n+1) is strictly monotonically increasing.
formula: a(n) = ((a(n-1) OR a(n-2)) + 1) AND NOT a(n-1). - _Charlie Neder_, Oct 12 2018

A051150.name: Generalized Stirling number triangle of first kind.
formula: E.g.f. for the m-th column of the signed triangle: (log(1 + 5*x)/5)^m/m!.
a(n, m) = S1(n, m)*5^(n-m), with S1(n, m) := A008275(n, m) (signed Stirling1 triangle).

A051151.name: Generalized Stirling number triangle of first kind.
formula: E.g.f. for the m-th column of the signed triangle: (log(1 + 6*x)/6)^m)/m!.
a(n, m) = S1(n, m)*6^(n-m), with S1(n, m) := A008275(n, m) (signed Stirling1 triangle).

A051152.name: (-1)sigma sociable number of order 2: (-1)sigma((-1)sigma(x))=x, but (-1)sigma(x)<>x, where if x=Product p(i)^r(i) then (-1)sigma(x)=Product (-1+Sum p(i)^s(i), s(i)=1 to r(i)); (-1)sigma(1)=1.

A051153.name: (-1)-sigma super perfect numbers: (-1)sigma((-1)sigma(x))=2*x, where if x=Product p(i)^r(i) then (-1)sigma(x)=Product (-1+Sum p(i)^s(i), s(i)=1 to r(i)); (-1)sigma(1)=1.

A051156.name: a(n) = (2^p^2 - 1)/(2^p - 1) where p is the n-th prime.
formula: a(n) = A070526(prime(n)), a(n) = A019320(prime(n)^2). - _Thomas Ordowski_, Feb 18 2014

A051158.name: Decimal expansion of Sum_{n >= 0} 1/(2^2^n+1).
formula: Equals (1/2) * Sum_{k>=1} A000120(k)/2^k (S. Audinarayana Moorthy, 1974). - _Amiram Eldar_, May 15 2020

A051159.name: Triangular array made of three copies of Pascal's triangle.
formula: T(n, k) = T(n-1, k-1) + T(n-1, k) if n odd or k even, else 0. T(0, 0) = 1.

Square array made by setting first row/column to 1's (A(i, 0) = A(0, j) = 1); A(1, 1) = 0; A(1, j) = A(1, j-2); A(i, 1) = A(i-2, 1); other entries A(i, j) = A(i-2, j) + A(i, j-2). - _Gerald McGarvey_, Aug 21 2004
Sum_{k=0..n} k * T(n,k) = A093968(n); A093968 = S-D transform of A001477. - _Philippe Deléham_, Aug 02 2006
Equals 2*A034851 - A007318. - _Gary W. Adamson_, Dec 31 2007. [Corrected by _Yosu Yurramendi_, Aug 07 2008]
Sum_{k = 0..n} T(n,k)*x^k = A000012(n), A016116(n+1), A056487(n), A136859(n+2) for x = 0, 1, 2, 3 respectively. - _Philippe Deléham_, Mar 11 2014
For n,k >= 1, T(n, k) = 0 when n odd and k even; otherwise, T(n, k) = binomial(floor((n-1)/2), floor((k-1)/2)). - _Christian Barrientos_, Mar 14 2020

A051161.name: a(n) is the exponent of n-th prime in order (A003131) of Monster simple group.

A051162.name: Triangle T(n,k) = n+k, n >= 0, 0 <= k <= n.
formula: a(n-1) = (t - t^2+ 2n-2)/2, where t = floor((-1+sqrt(8*n-7))/2), n > 0. - _Robert G. Wilson v_ and _Boris Putievskiy_, Mar 14 2012
G.f.: x/(1-x)^2 + (1-x)^(-1)*Sum(j>=1, (1-j)*x^A000217(j)).  The sum is related to Jacobi Theta functions. (End)

A051163.name: Sequence is defined by property that (a0,a1,a2,a3,...) = binomial transform of (a0,a0,a1,a1,a2,a2,a3,a3,...).
formula: a(n) = 1 + Sum_{k=1..n} Sum_{j=0..n-k} C(k, j)*C(n-k, j)*a(j). - _Paul D. Hanna_, Nov 22 2004
G.f. A(x) satisfies: A(x) = A(x^2/(1-x)^2)/(1-x)^2 and A(x^2) = A(x/(1+x))/(1+x)^2. - _Paul D. Hanna_, Nov 22 2004

A051164.name: Sequence is defined by property that (a0,a1,a2,a3,...) = binomial transform of (a0,a0,a0,a1,a1,a1,a2,a2,a2,a3,a3,a3,...).

A051165.name: Sequence is defined by property that binomial transform of (a0,a1,a2,a3,...) = (a0,a0,a1,a1,a2,a2,a3,a3,...).

A051166.name: Sequence is defined by property that binomial transform of (a0,a1,a2,a3,...) = (a0,a0,a0,a1,a1,a1,a2,a2,a2,a3,a3,a3,...).

A051167.name: Sum of two positive cubes in at least five ways (all solutions).

A051168.name: Triangular array T(h,k) for 0 <= k <= h read by rows: T(h,k) = number of binary Lyndon words with k ones and h-k zeros.
formula: T(h, k) = 1 for (h, k) in {(0, 0), (1, 0), (1, 1)}; T(h, k) = 0 if h >= 2 and k = 0 or k = h. Otherwise, T(h, k) = (1/h)*(C(h, k)-S(h, k)), where S(h, k) = Sum_{d <= 2, d|h, d|k} (h/d)*T(h/d, k/d).
1 - x - y = Product_{i,j} (1 - x^i * y^j)^T(i+j, j) where i >= 0, j >= 0 are not both zero. - _Michael Somos_, Jul 03 2004

The prime rows are given by (1+x)^p/p with noninteger coefficients rounded to zero. E.g., for h = 2 below, (1 + x)^2/2 = (1 + 2*x + x^2)/2 = 0.5 + x + 0.5*x^2 gives (0,1,0). - _Tom Copeland_, Oct 21 2014
T(n,k) = (1/n) * Sum_{d | gcd(n,k)} mu(d) * binomial(n/d, k/d), for n > 0. - _Andrew Howroyd_, Mar 26 2017
O.g.f. for column k >= 1: (x^k/k) * Sum_{d|k} mu(d)/(1 - x^d)^(k/d).
Bivariate o.g.f.: Sum_{n,k >= 0} T(n, k)*x^n*y^k = 1 - Sum_{d >= 1} (mu(d)/d) *log(1 - x^d * (1 + y^d)).

A051169.name: Smallest number m such that 2*m - p is composite for the first n primes p.

A051170.name: T(n,5), array T as in A051168; a count of Lyndon words; aperiodic necklaces with 5 black beads and n-5 white beads.

A051172.name: T(n,7), array T as in A051168; a count of Lyndon words; aperiodic necklaces with 7 black beads and n-7 white beads.

A051173.name: Triangular array T read by rows: T(u,v) = lcm(u,v).

A051175.name: Number of trees T of order n such that W(T) = W(L(L(T))) where W(G) and L(G) are the Wiener index and line graph of a graph G.

A051176.name: If n mod 3 = 0 then n/3 else n.
formula: a(n) = A109044(n)/3. Dirichlet g.f. zeta(s-1)*(1-2/3^s). - _R. J. Mathar_, Apr 18 2011
a(n) = a(-n) for all n in Z. - _Michael Somos_, Mar 05 2017

A051177.name: Perfectly partitioned numbers: numbers n such that n divides the number of partitions p(n) of n.

A051178.name: Numbers k such that k divides number of divisors of k!.
formula: It seems that a(n) is asymptotic to c*n with c=3.2..... - _Benoit Cloitre_, Sep 03 2002
No member > 2 is prime. - _Charlie Neder_, Dec 23 2018

A051179.name: a(n) = 2^(2^n) - 1.
formula: a(n) = b(n-1) where b(1)=1, b(n) = Product_{k=1..n-1} (b(k) + 2). - _Benoit Cloitre_, Sep 13 2003

A051180.name: Number of 3-element intersecting families of an n-element set.

A051181.name: Number of 4-element intersecting families of an n-element set.

A051182.name: Number of 5-element intersecting families of an n-element set.

A051183.name: Number of 6-element intersecting families of an n-element set.

A051184.name: Number of 7-element intersecting families of an n-element set.

A051185.name: Number of intersecting families of an n-element set. Also number of n-variable clique Boolean functions.

A051186.name: Generalized Stirling number triangle of first kind.
formula: E.g.f. for m-th column of signed triangle: (log(1 + 7*x)/7)^m/m!.
a(n,m) = 7^(n-m)*S1(n,m) with the (signed) Stirling1 triangle S1(n,m) = A008275(n,m).
Bivariate e.g.f.-o.g.f.: Sum_{n,m >= 1} a(n,m)*x^n*y^m/n! = exp((y/7)*log(1 + 7*x)) - 1 = (1 + 7*x)^(y/7) - 1. - _Petros Hadjicostas_, Jun 07 2020

A051187.name: Generalized Stirling number triangle of the first kind.
formula: E.g.f. for the m-th column of the signed triangle: (log(1 + 8*x)/8)^m/m!.

A051190.name: a(n) = Product_{k=1..n-1} gcd(k,n).
formula: a(n) = Product_{ d divides n, d < n } d^phi(n/d). - _Peter Luschny_, Apr 07 2013
Product_{j=1..n} Product_{k=1..j-1} gcd(j,k), n >= 1. - _Daniel Forgues_, Apr 11 2013

A051192.name: T(n,7), array T as in A050186; a count of aperiodic binary words.

A051193.name: a(n) = Sum_{k=1..n} lcm(n,k).
formula: a(n) = n*(1+Sum_{d|n} d*phi(d))/2 = n*(1+A057660(n))/2 = n*A057661(n). - _Vladeta Jovovic_, Jun 21 2002
G.f.: x*f'(x), where f(x) = x/(2*(1 - x)) + (1/2)*Sum_{k>=1} k*phi(k)*x^k/(1 - x^k) and phi() is the Euler totient function (A000010). - _Ilya Gutkovskiy_, Aug 31 2017
Sum_{k=1..n} a(k) ~ 3 * zeta(3) * n^4 / (4*Pi^2). - _Vaclav Kotesovec_, May 29 2021

A051194.name: Triangular array T read by rows: T(n,k) = number of positive integers that divide both n and k.
formula: T(n,k) = T(k,n) = T(-n,k) = T(n,-k) = T(n,n+k) = T(n+k,k). - _Michael Somos_, Jul 18 2011

A051195.name: T(2n+2,n), array T as in A050186; a count of aperiodic binary words.
formula: C(2n+2, n)-[n even]*C(n+1, n/2). - _Ralf Stephan_, Mar 19 2004

A051196.name: T(2n+3,n), array T as in A050186; a count of aperiodic binary words.

A051197.name: T(2n+4,n), array T as in A050186; a count of aperiodic binary words.

A051198.name: T(2n+5,n), array T as in A050186; a count of aperiodic binary words.

A051199.name: T(2n+6,n), array T as in A050186; a count of aperiodic binary words.

A051200.name: Except for initial term, primes of form "n 3's followed by 1".

A051201.name: Sum of elements of the set { [ n/k ] : 1 <= k <= n }.
formula: a(n) = m*(m+1)/2 + Sum_{k=1..floor(n/(m+1))} floor(n/k), where m is the largest number such that m*(m+1) <= n, i.e., m=floor( (sqrt(4*n+1)-1)/2 ). - _Max Alekseyev_, Feb 12 2012

A051204.name: Nonnegative numbers of the form x^2-2^y.

A051209.name: Nonnegative numbers of the form x^2-7^y.

A051217.name: Nonnegative numbers of the form 6^x - y^2.

A051222.name: Numbers n such that Bernoulli number B_{n} has denominator 6.

A051223.name: Number of ways of placing n nonattacking superqueens on an n X n board.

A051224.name: Number of ways of placing n nonattacking superqueens on n X n board (symmetric solutions count only once).
formula: a(n) = (1/8) * (Q(n) + P(n) + 2 * R(n)), where Q(n) = A051223(n) [all solutions], P(n) [point symmetric solutions (180 degrees)] and R(n) [rotationally symmetric solutions (90 degrees)]. This formula has the same structure as the formula for A002562. There seem to be no OEIS sequences (yet) for P(n) and R(n). See http://m29s20.vlinux.de/~wschub/nqueen.html for a few terms. - _W. Schubert_, Nov 29 2009

A051225.name: Numbers m such that the Bernoulli number B_{2*m} has denominator 30.

A051226.name: Numbers m such that the Bernoulli number B_m has denominator 30.

A051227.name: Numbers m such that the Bernoulli number B_{2*m} has denominator 42.

A051228.name: Numbers m such that the Bernoulli number B_m has denominator 42.

A051229.name: Numbers m such that the Bernoulli number B_{2*m} has denominator 66.

A051230.name: Numbers m such that the Bernoulli number B_m has denominator 66.

A051231.name: Generalized Stirling number triangle of the first kind.
formula: E.g.f. for the m-th column of the signed triangle: (log(1 + 9*x)/9)^m/m!.

A051233.name: Number of unit squares at least 50% covered by a circle inscribed in an integer square of size n X n.

A051234.name: Possible orders of central factor groups of groups.

A051235.name: Number of distinct most-perfect pandiagonal magic squares of order 4n in the Frenicle standard form.
formula: For n >= 1, let N := 4n = Product_{g} (p_g)^(s_g), where p_g are distinct primes, and W_v(n) := Sum_{i=0..v} (-1)^(v+i) * binomial(v+1,i+1) * Product_{g} binomial(s_g+i,i). Then a(n) = 2^(N-2) * (2n)!^2 * Sum_{v=0..Sum_{g} s_g} W_v(N)*(W_v(N)+W_{v+1}(N)). - _Floor van Lamoen_, Aug 16 2001; corrected by _Max Alekseyev_, Jul 02 2019

A051236.name: Largest integer a(n) for which the integer interval [ 0,a(n) ] is a subset of the set of determinants of all n X n 0-1 matrices.

A051237.name: Lexicographically earliest prime pyramid, read by rows.

A051238.name: First appearance of string n in e.

A051239.name: Number of ways to arrange integers 1 through n so that the sum of each adjacent pair is prime, not counting reversals.

A051240.name: Number of 4-uniform hypergraphs on n unlabeled nodes, or equivalently pure 3-dimensional simplicial complexes on n unlabeled nodes.

A051241.name: Number of relations with 5 arguments on n nodes.

A051242.name: Array T by antidiagonals; T(n,k)=k-th binary number d(1),...,d(j) for which exactly n digits d(i) satisfy d(i)=d(j+1-i) (n=0,1,2,...; k=1,2,3,..).

A051243.name: Base 3 numbers d(1)...d(j) such that d(i)=d(j+1-i) for all but 2 i.

A051244.name: Binary numbers d(1)...d(j) such that d(i)<>d(j+1-i) for all but two i.

A051245.name: Binary numbers d(1)...d(j) such that d(i)=d(j+1-i) for all but two i.

A051246.name: Binary numbers d(1)...d(j) such that d(i)=d(j+1-k) for all but 4 i.

A051247.name: Binary numbers d(1)...d(j) such that d(i)<>d(j+1-k) for all but 4 i.

A051248.name: n^a(n) is smallest power of n (with a(n) > 1) which starts with n.

A051249.name: Pure 4-dimensional simplicial complexes on n unlabeled nodes.

A051250.name: Numbers whose reduced residue system consists of 1 and prime powers only.

A051252.name: Number of essentially different ways of arranging numbers 1 through 2n around a circle so that sum of each pair of adjacent numbers is prime.

A051253.name: Weights of rotation-symmetric functions in n variables.

A051254.name: Mills primes.
formula: a(1) = 2; a(n) is least prime > a(n-1)^3. - _Jonathan Vos Post_, May 05 2006

A051255.name: Number of cyclically symmetric transpose complement plane partitions in a 2n X 2n X 2n box.
formula: a(n) = Product_{i=0..n-1} (3i+1) C(6i,2i)/(C(4i+1,2i)*(2i+1)), using [Bressoud, Corrections, p. 199: N8]. - _M. F. Hasler_, Oct 04 2018

A051256.name: Numbers formed from binomial coefficients (mod 2) interpreted as digits in factorial base.

A051257.name: Numbers formed from binomial coefficients (mod 2+k) interpreted as digits in factorial base.

A051258.name: Fibocyclotomic numbers: numbers formed from cyclotomic polynomials and Fibonacci numbers (A000045).
formula: a(n) = Sum (coefficient_of_term_i_of_cp_n times Fib(exponent_of_term_i_of_cp_n)), i=1..degree of cp_n, where cp_n is the n-th cyclotomic polynomial.

A051261.name: Main diagonal of A018219, i.e., (n, n, a_n) is a winning position.

A051263.name: Expansion of 1/((1-x)*(1-x^3)^2*(1-x^5)).
formula: A029153(n) = a(floor(n/2) - mod(n,2)) = a(A028242(n - 2)). - _Michael Somos_, Mar 21 2003

A051265.name: Maximal value of prime divisors of numbers in reduced residue system for n.
formula: a(n) << log n/log log n. - _Charles R Greathouse IV_, Aug 10 2017

A051266.name: Numbers n such that maximal value of prime divisors of reduced residue system for n is 2.

A051267.name: Numbers n such that maximal value of prime divisors of reduced residue system for n is 3.

A051268.name: Numbers n such that maximal value of prime divisors of reduced residue system for n is 4.

A051269.name: Number of self-complementary 3-place relations on a 2n-element set.

A051270.name: Numbers that are divisible by exactly 5 different primes.

A051271.name: Number of numbers either relatively prime to or divisors of primorial number(n).

A051272.name: Number of numbers neither relatively prime to nor divisors of primorial number(n).
formula: a(n) = primorial(n) - (phi(primorial(n)) + tau(primorial(n)) - 1). - _Michael De Vlieger_, Feb 04 2015

A051273.name: Expansion of q^(-1/3) * b(q) * c(q) / a(q)^2 in powers of q where a(), b(), c() are cubic AGM theta functions.
formula: Expansion of 3*(eta(q)*eta(q^3))^2/(theta[A_2](q)^2*q^(1/3)) in powers of q.

A051274.name: Expansion of (1+x^4)/((1-x^2)*(1-x^3)).
formula: a(n) = 2*floor(n/2) + floor(n/3) - n + 1. Also a(0) = 1 and a(1) = 0, a(n) = a(n-2) + (a(n-1) reduced = (mod 2)). Again, a(0) = 1, a(1) = 0, a(n) = a(n-1) - 1 - (-1)^n - (a(n-2) mod 2). - _Benoit Cloitre_ and _Philippe Deléham_, Jan 17 2004
a(n) = a(n-2) + a(n-3) - a(n-5). - _Philippe Deléham_, Sep 14 2006
Euler transform of length 8 sequence [ 0, 1, 1, 1, 0, 0, 0, -1]. - _Michael Somos_, Sep 26 2006

A051275.name: Expansion of (1+x^2)/((1-x^2)*(1-x^3)).
formula: a(n) = Sum_{k=0..floor(n/2)} F(L((n-2k+2)/3)) where L(j/p) is the Legendre symbol of j and p. (End)

A051276.name: Nonzero coefficients in one of the 5-adic expansions of sqrt(-1).

A051278.name: Numbers n such that n = k/d(k) has a unique solution, where d(k) = number of divisors of k.

A051279.name: Numbers n such that n = k/d(k) has exactly 2 solutions, where d(k) = number of divisors of k.

A051280.name: Numbers n such that n = k/d(k) has exactly 3 solutions, where d(k) = number of divisors of k.

A051281.name: Sum of divisors of n, sigma(n) (A000203), is a power of number of divisors of n, d(n) (A000005).

A051282.name: 2-adic valuation of A025487: largest k such that 2^k divides A025487(n), where A025487 gives products of primorials.

A051283.name: Numbers k such that if one writes k = Product p_i^e_i (p_i primes) and P = max p_i^e_i, then k/P > P.

A051284.name: Relative minima of n/c(n), where c(n) is Hofstadter-Conway sequence A004001.

A051286.name: Whitney number of level n of the lattice of the ideals of the fence of order 2n.
formula: a(n) = Sum_{k=0..floor(n/2)} binomial(n-k, k)*(-1)^k*A002426(n-2k). - _Paul Barry_, Jan 31 2005
a(n) = Sum_{k=0..n} A049310(n, k)^2. - _Philippe Deléham_, Nov 21 2005
G.f.: exp( Sum_{n>=1} (x^n/n)*Sum_{k=0..n} C(2n,2k)*x^k ). - _Paul D. Hanna_, Mar 18 2011
Logarithmic derivative equals A185828. - _Paul D. Hanna_, Mar 18 2011
D-finite with recurrence: n*a(n) - (2*n-1)*a(n-1) - (n-1)*a(n-2) - (2*n-3)*a(n-3) + (n-2)*a(n-4) = 0. - _R. J. Mathar_, Dec 17 2011
The g.f. A(x) satisfies the differential equation (1-2*x-x^2-2*x^3+x^4)*A'(x) = (1+x+3*x^2-2*x^3)*A(x), from which the recurrence conjectured by Mathar follows. - _Emanuele Munarini_, Dec 18 2017
a(n) ~ phi^(2*n + 2) / (2 * 5^(1/4) * sqrt(Pi*n)), where phi = A001622 = (1 + sqrt(5))/2 is the golden ratio. - _Vaclav Kotesovec_, Jan 05 2013, simplified Dec 18 2017
G.f.: Sum_{n>=0} x^n * Sum_{k=0..n} C(n,k)^2 * x^k.

A051287.name: Triangular array T read by rows: T(n,k)=P(n,k,|n-2k|), where P(n,k,c)=number of vectors (x(1),x(2,),...,x(n)) of k 1's and n-k 0's such that x(i)=x(n+1-i) for exactly c values of i.

A051288.name: Triangle read by rows: T(n,k) = number of paths of n upsteps U and n downsteps D that contain k UUDs.

A051289.name: Triangular array T read by rows: T(n,k)=P(2n+1,n,2k+1), where P(n,k,c)=number of vectors (x(1),x(2,),...,x(n)) of k 1's and n-k 0's such that x(i)=x(n+1-i) for exactly c values of i.

A051290.name: Triangular array T read by rows: T(n,k)=P(2n+3,n,2k+3), where P(n,k,c)=number of vectors (x(1),x(2,),...,x(n)) of k 1's and n-k 0's such that x(i)=x(n+1-i) for exactly c values of i.

A051291.name: Whitney number of level n of the lattice of the ideals of the fence of order 2 n + 1.

A051292.name: Whitney number of level n of the lattice of the ideals of the crown of size 2 n.
formula: a(n) = sum{k=0..floor(n/2), (n/(n-k))C(n-k, k)*(-1)^k*sum{i=0..floor((n-2k)/2), C(n-2k, 2i)C(2i, i)}}; a(n)=sum{k=0..floor(n/2), (n/(n-k))C(n-k, k)*(-1)^k*A002426(n-2k)}. - _Paul Barry_, Jan 31 2005

Conjecture confirmed using the differential equation (2*x^2-x+2)*y(x) + (4*x^4-5*x^3-x^2+x-2)*y'(x) + (x^5-2*x^4-x^3-2*x^2+x)*y''(x) - 2*x^2 + x - 2 = 0 satisfied by the g.f. - _Robert Israel_, Dec 06 2017

A051293.name: Number of nonempty subsets of {1,2,3,...,n} whose elements have an integer average.

A051294.name: a(n) = F(n^2)/F(n), where F(n) = A000045(n) is the n-th Fibonacci number.
formula: a(n) = [x^(n-1)] 1/(1 - Lucas(n)*x + (-1)^n*x^2), where Lucas(n) = A000204(n). - _Paul D. Hanna_, Jan 28 2012

A051295.name: a(0)=1; thereafter, a(m+1) = Sum_{k=0..m} k!*a(m-k).
formula: It appears that the INVERT transform of factorial numbers A000142 gives 1, 2, 5, 15, 54, 235, 1237, ... - _Antti Karttunen_, May 30 2003
This is true: translating the defining recurrence to a generating function identity yields A(x)=  1/(1 - (0!x + 1!x^2 + 2!x^3 + ...)) which is the INVERT formula.
In other words: let F(x) = Sum_{n>=0} n!*x^n then the g.f. is 1/(1-x*F(x)), cf. A052186 (g.f. F(x)/(1+x*F(x))). - _Joerg Arndt_, Apr 25 2011
a(n) = Sum_{k>=0} A084938(n, k). - _Philippe Deléham_, Feb 05 2004
G.f. A(x) satisfies: A(x) = (1-x)*A(x)^2 - x^2*A'(x). - _Paul D. Hanna_, Aug 02 2008
a(n) = upper left term in M^n, M = an infinite square production matrix in which a column of 1's is prepended to Pascal's triangle, as follows:
Also, a(n+1) = sum of top row terms of M^n. (End)
G.f.: 1+x/(U(0)-x) where U(k) = 1 + x*k - x*(k+1)/U(k+1); (continued fraction, 1-step). - _Sergei N. Gladkovskii_, Oct 10 2012
G.f.: 1/(U(0) - x) where U(k) = 1 - x*(k+1)/(1 - x*(k+1)/U(k+1)); (continued fraction, 2-step). - _Sergei N. Gladkovskii_, Nov 12 2012

A051296.name: INVERT transform of factorial numbers.
formula: a(0) = 1; a(n) = Sum_{k=1..n} a(n-k)*k! for n>0.
a(n) = Sum_{k>=0} A090238(n, k). - _Philippe Deléham_, Feb 05 2004
a(n) is the upper left term of M^n, M = an infinite square production matrix as follows:
G.f.: 1 + x/(G(0) - 2*x) where G(k) = 1 + (k+1)*x - x*(k+2)/G(k+1); (recursively defined continued fraction). - _Sergei N. Gladkovskii_, Dec 26 2012

A051299.name: a(n+1) = a(n) + rotate( a(n), 1 digit left).

A051300.name: a(n+1) = a(n) + rotate( a(n), 1 digit right).

A051301.name: Smallest prime factor of n!+1.
formula: Erdős & Stewart show that a(n) > n + (l-o(l))log n/log log n except when n + 1 is prime, and that a(n) > n + e(n)sqrt(n) for almost all n where e(n) is any function with lim e(n) = 0. - _Charles R Greathouse IV_, Dec 05 2012
By Wilson's theorem, a(n) >=  n + 1 with equality if and only if n + 1 is prime. - _Chai Wah Wu_, Jul 14 2019

The sequence b(n) := (2*n - 2)! also satisfies Mathar's recurrence with b(1) = 1, b(2) = 2. This leads to the continued fraction representation a(n) = (2*n - 2)!*(1 + 1/(2 - 2/(13 - 12/(31 - ... - (2*n - 4)*(2*n - 5)/(4*n^2 - 10*n + 7) )))) for n >= 3. Taking the limit gives the continued fraction representation cosh(1) = A073743 = 1 + 1/(2 - 2/(13 - 12/(31 - ... - (2*n - 4)*(2*n - 5)/((4*n^2 - 10*n + 7) - ... )))). (End)

A051397.name: a(n) = (2*n-2)*(2*n-1)*a(n-1)+1.

Mathar's conjectured recurrence a(n) = (4*n^2 - 6*n + 3)*a(n-1) - (2*n - 3)*(2*n - 4)*a(n-2) follows easily from the defining recurrence. The sequence b(n) := (2*n - 1)! also satisfies Mathar's recurrence but with b(1) = 1, b(2) = 6. This leads to the continued fraction representation a(n) = (2*n - 1)!*(1 + 1/(6 - 6/(21 - 20/(43 - ... - (2*n - 3)*(2*n - 4)/(4*n^2 - 6*n + 3) )))) for n >= 3. Taking the limit gives the continued fraction representation sinh(1) = A073742 = 1 + 1/(6 - 6/(21 - 20/(43 - ... - (2*n - 3)*(2*n - 4)/((4*n^2 - 6*n + 3) - ... )))). (End)

A051557.name: Decimal expansion of cos(Pi/2 degrees). (Of course, cos(Pi/2 radians) = 0.)

A051558.name: Decimal expansion of sin(Pi/2 degrees). (Of course, sin(Pi/2 radians) = 1.)

A051559.name: Decimal expansion of tan(Pi/2 degrees). (Of course, tan(Pi/2 radians) = infinity.)

A051560.name: Second unsigned column of triangle A051379.
formula: a(n) = n!*Sum_{k=0..n-1} ((-1)^k*binomial(-8,k)/(n-k)), for n>=1. - _Milan Janjic_, Dec 14 2008
a(n) = n!*[7]h(n), where [k]h(n) denotes the k-th successive summation of the harmonic numbers from 0 to n. - _Gary Detlefs_ Jan 04 2011

A051561.name: Third unsigned column of triangle A051379.
formula: If we define f(n,i,a)=sum(binomial(n,k)*stirling1(n-k,i)*product(-a-j,j=0..k-1),k=0..n-i), then a(n) = |f(n,2,8)|, for n>=1. - _Milan Janjic_, Dec 21 2008

A051562.name: Second unsigned column of triangle A051380.
formula: a(n) = n!*Sum_{k=0..n-1} ((-1)^k*binomial(-9,k)/(n-k)), for n>=1. - _Milan Janjic_, Dec 14 2008
a(n) = n!*[8]h(n), where [k]h(n) denotes the k-th successive summation of the harmonic numbers from 0 to n. - _Gary Detlefs_ Jan 04 2011

A051563.name: Third unsigned column of triangle A051380.
formula: If we define f(n,i,a)=sum(binomial(n,k)*stirling1(n-k,i)*product(-a-j,j=0..k-1),k=0..n-i), then a(n) = |f(n,2,9)|, for n>=1. - _Milan Janjic_, Dec 21 2008

A051564.name: Second unsigned column of triangle A051523.
formula: a(n) = n!*[9]h(n), where [k]h(n) denotes the k-th successive summation of the harmonic numbers from 0 to n. - _Gary Detlefs_ Jan 04 2011

A051565.name: Third unsigned column of triangle A051523.
formula: If we define f(n,i,a)=sum(binomial(n,k)*stirling1(n-k,i)*product(-a-j,j=0..k-1),k=0..n-i), then a(n) = |f(n,2,10)|, for n>=1. - _Milan Janjic_, Dec 21 2008

A051567.name: Consider problem of placing N queens on an n X n board so that each queen attacks precisely k others. Here k=1 and sequence gives number of inequivalent solutions when N is equal to the upper bound 2*floor(2n/3).

A051568.name: Let M(n) (A051755) be the maximal number of queens that can be placed on an n X n chessboard so that each queen attacks exactly two other queens; a(n) is the number of non-equivalent solutions. "Non-equivalent" means none of the a(n) solutions can be mapped onto any other solution by board rotations through 90, 180 or 270 degrees or mirror operations along the two diagonals or center lines.

A051569.name: Consider the problem of placing N = A051756(n) queens on an n X n board so that each queen attacks precisely 3 others; a(n) gives the number of inequivalent solutions.

A051570.name: Consider the problem of placing N queens on an n X n board so that each queen attacks precisely k others. Here k=3 and sequence gives number of different solutions when N takes its maximal value.

A051571.name: Consider problem of placing N queens on an n X n board so that each queen attacks precisely k others. Here k=4 and sequence gives number of different solutions when N takes its maximal value.

A051574.name: a(n) = number of k, 1<=k<=n, such that (n*k) divides binomial(n,k).

A051576.name: Order of Burnside group B(3,n) of exponent 3 and rank n.

A051577.name: a(n) = (2*n + 3)!!/3 = A001147(n+2)/3.
formula: Ramanujan polynomials -psi_n(n, x) evaluated at 0. - _Ralf Stephan_, Apr 16 2004
a(n) = 2^(2 + n) * Gamma(n + 5/2)/(3 * sqrt(Pi)). - _Gerson Washiski Barbosa_, May 05 2010
D-finite with recurrence a(n+1) = (2*n + 5)*a(n) with a(0) = 1.
O.g.f. A(x) satisfies the Riccati differential equation 2*x^2*A(x)' = (1 - 5*x)*A(x) - 1 with A(0) = 1.

A051578.name: a(n) = (2*n+4)!!/4!!, related to A000165 (even double factorials).
formula: a(n) = (n+2)!*2^(n-1). - _Zerinvary Lajos_, Sep 23 2006. [corrected by _Gary Detlefs_, Apr 29 2019]
O.g.f. satisfies the Riccati differential equation 2*x^2*A(x)' = (1 - 6*x)*A(x) - 1 with A(0) = 1.

A051579.name: a(n) = (2*n+5)!!/5!!, related to A001147 (odd double factorials).
formula: G.f.: G(0)/(10*x) -1/(5*x), where G(k)= 1 + 1/(1 - x*(2*k+5)/(x*(2*k+5) + 1/G(k+1))); (continued fraction). - _Sergei N. Gladkovskii_, Jun 13 2013
O.g.f. satisfies the Riccati differential equation 2*x^2*A(x)' = (1 - 7*x)*A(x) - 1 with A(0) = 1.

A051580.name: a(n) = (2*n+6)!!/6!!, related to A000165 (even double factorials).
formula: G.f.: G(0)/2, where G(k)= 1 + 1/(1 - x/(x + 1/(2*k+8)/G(k+1))); (continued fraction). - _Sergei N. Gladkovskii_, Jun 02 2013
O.g.f. satisfies the Riccati differential equation 2*x^2*A(x)' = (1 - 8*x)*A(x) - 1 with A(0) = 1.

A051581.name: a(n) = (2*n+7)!!/7!!, related to A001147 (odd double factorials).
formula: G.f.: G(0)/2, where G(k)= 1 + 1/(1 - x/(x + 1/(2*k+9)/G(k+1))); (continued fraction). - _Sergei N. Gladkovskii_, Jun 02 2013
O.g.f. satisfies the Riccati differential equation 2*x^2*A(x)' = (1 - 9*x)*A(x) - 1 with A(0) = 1.

A051582.name: a(n) = (2*n+8)!!/8!!, related to A000165 (even double factorials).
formula: O.g.f. satisfies the Riccati differential equation 2*x^2*A(x)' = (1 - 10*x)*A(x) - 1 with A(0) = 1.

A051583.name: a(n) = (2*n+9)!!/9!!, related to A001147 (odd double factorials).
formula: O.g.f. satisfies the Riccati differential equation 2*x^2*A(x)' = (1 - 11*x)*A(x) - 1 with A(0) = 1.

A051584.name: Number of integer-sided triangles of area n.

A051585.name: Number of integer-sided triangles of area 6n.

A051586.name: There are exactly n integer-sided triangles of area a(n).

A051587.name: Number of 4 X n binary matrices such that any 2 rows have a common 1.

A051588.name: Number of 3 X n binary matrices such that any 2 rows have a common 1.

A051589.name: Number of 5xn binary matrices such that any 2 rows have a common 1.

A051590.name: Number of oriented triangle graphs on binomial(n,2) points.
formula: There is a formula for n <> 4 in the reference, too complicated to repeat here.

A051591.name: Number of oriented triangle graphs with transitively oriented maximal cliques, on binomial(n,2) points.
formula: a(n) = Sum_{d|n} { d^d * ( (n-1)! )^d / ( n^d * d!) }, valid for n > 4.

A051592.name: Numbers n such that n!!!!!!-1 is prime.

A051593.name: Largest order of even permutation of n elements, or maximal order of element of alternating group A_n.

A051594.name: Maximal elements of pairs of "(-1)sigma amicable numbers", sorted by their minimal elements.
formula: (-1)sigma(a) = (-1)sigma(b) = a+b where a<b. Here (-1)sigma(n) = A049060(n): If n = Product p(i)^r(i) then (-1)sigma(n) = Product(-1+Sum p(i)^s, s=1 to r(i)). This sequence gives the values of b; A051595 gives the values of a.

A051595.name: Minimal elements of pairs of "(-1)sigma amicable numbers", sorted by their minimal elements.
formula: (-1)sigma(a) = (-1)sigma(b) = a+b where a<b. Here (-1)sigma(n) = A049060(n): If n = Product p(i)^r(i) then (-1)sigma(n) = Product(-1+Sum p(i)^s, s=1 to r(i)). This sequence gives the values of a; A051594 gives the values of b.

A051596.name: Numerical values or Gematriahs of Hebrew letters {aleph, bet, ..., tav}.

A051597.name: Rows of triangle formed using Pascal's rule except begin and end n-th row with n+1.
formula: T(m,n) = binomial(m+n,m) - binomial(m+n-2,m-1) (correct up to offset and transformation of square indices to triangular indices). - _Bridget Tenner_, Nov 09 2007
T(n,k) = binomial(n,k-1) + binomial(n,k) + binomial(n,k+1) for 0 <= k <= n.

A051598.name: Rows of triangle formed using Pascal's rule except begin n-th row with n+1 and end it with n+2.

A051599.name: Rows of triangle formed using Pascal's rule except begin and end n-th row with (n+1)st prime.

A051600.name: Rows of triangle formed using Pascal's rule except begin n-th row with (n+1)st prime and end it with (n+2)nd prime.

A051601.name: Rows of triangle formed using Pascal's rule except we begin and end the n-th row with n.
formula: T(m,n) = binomial(m+n,m) - 2*binomial(m+n-2,m-1), up to offset and transformation of array to triangular indices. - _Bridget Tenner_, Nov 10 2007
T(n,k) = binomial(n, k+1) + binomial(n, n-k+1). - _Roger L. Bagula_, Feb 17 2009

A051602.name: Maximal number of squares that can be formed from n points in the plane.

A051603.name: Expansion of square of g.f. for A051573.

A051606.name: a(n) = (3*n+6)!!!/6!!!, related to A032031 ((3*n)!!! triple factorials).

A051607.name: a(n) = (3*n+7)!!!/7!!!, related to A007559(n+1) ((3*n+1)!!! triple factorials).

A051608.name: a(n) = (3*n+8)!!!/8!!!, related to A008544(n+1) ((3*n+2)!!! triple factorials).

A051609.name: a(n) = (3*n+9)!!!/9!!!, related to A032031 ((3*n)!!! triple factorials).

A051611.name: Numbers that are not the sum of 2 nonzero triangular numbers.

A051612.name: a(n) = sigma(n) - phi(n).
formula: a(n) > 1 for n > 1; a(n) = 2 if and only if n is prime. - _Charles R Greathouse IV_, May 09 2013
G.f.: Sum_{k>=1} (1 - mu(k))*x^k/(1 - x^k)^2. - _Ilya Gutkovskiy_, Sep 29 2017

A051613.name: a(n) = partitions of n into powers of distinct primes (1 not considered a power).
formula: a(n) = number of m such that A008475(m) = n.

A051614.name: 4th term in Euclid-Mullin prime sequence started with n-th prime (cf. A000945).

A051615.name: Primes for which A051614 is 3.
formula: Odd p values such that F(2*p*F(2*p+1)+1)=3, where F(x) is the least prime divisor of x.

A051616.name: Primes for which A051614 is 3 but are not in A005834.
formula: p values so that F(2*p*F(2*p+1)+1)=3 and 2p+1 is not prime; F(x) is the least prime divisor of x.

A051617.name: a(n) = (4*n+5)(!^4)/5(!^4), related to A007696(n+1) ((4*n+1)(!^4) quartic, or 4-factorials).

A051618.name: a(n) = (4*n+6)(!^4)/6(!^4).
formula: G.f.: G(0)/2, where G(k)= 1 + 1/(1 - 2*x/(2*x + 1/(2*k+5)/G(k+1))); (continued fraction). - _Sergei N. Gladkovskii_, Jun 02 2013

A051619.name: a(n) = (4*n+7)(!^4)/7(!^4), related to A034176(n+1) ((4*n+3)(!^4) quartic, or 4-factorials).

A051620.name: a(n) = (4*n+8)(!^4)/8(!^4), related to A034177(n+1) ((4*n+4)(!^4) quartic, or 4-factorials).
formula: G.f.: G(0)/2, where G(k)= 1 + 1/(1 - 2*x/(2*x + 1/(2*k+6)/G(k+1))); (continued fraction). - _Sergei N. Gladkovskii_, Jun 02 2013

A051621.name: a(n) = (4*n+9)(!^4)/9(!^4), related to A007696(n+1) ((4*n+1)(!^4) quartic, or 4-factorials).

A051622.name: a(n) = (4*n+10)(!^4)/10(!^4), related to A000407 ((4*n+2)(!^4) quartic, or 4-factorials).
formula: G.f.: G(0)/2, where G(k)= 1 + 1/(1 - 2*x/(2*x + 1/(2*k+7)/G(k+1))); (continued fraction). - _Sergei N. Gladkovskii_, Jun 02 2013

A051624.name: 12-gonal (or dodecagonal) numbers: a(n) = n*(5*n-4).
formula: E.g.f.: x*(5*x + 1) * exp(x). - _G. C. Greubel_, Jul 31 2015
a(n) + 4*(n-1)^2 = (3*n-2)^2. Let P(k,n) be the n-th k-gonal number. Then, in general, P(4k,n) + (k-1)^2*(n-1)^2 = (k*n-k+1)^2. - _Charlie Marion_, Feb 04 2020

A051625.name: Number of "labeled" cyclic subgroups of symmetric group S_n.
formula: a(n) = Sum_{pi} n!/(k_1!*1^k_1*k_2!*2^k_2*...*k_n!*n^k_n*phi(lcm{i:k_i != 0})), where pi runs through all partitions k_1+2*k_2+...+n*k_n=n and phi is Euler's function.

A051626.name: Period of decimal representation of 1/n, or 0 if 1/n terminates.

A051628.name: Number of digits in decimal expansion of 1/n before the periodic part begins.
formula: for n>1, a(n)=max(i, j) where n=2^i*3^x*5^j*... is the prime decomposition of n.

A051629.name: Poincaré series [or Poincare series] for Gamma_2(1,2).

A051630.name: Poincaré series [or Poincare series] (or Molien series) for Gamma_2(1,2)_(2).

A051631.name: Triangle formed using Pascal's rule except begin and end n-th row with n-1.

A051632.name: Rows of triangle formed using Pascal's rule except we begin and end the n-th row with n-2.
formula: -t(n,k)=((2*k + 1 - n)/(k + 1))*Binomial[n, k] + ((1 - n + 2 (-k + n))/(1 - k + n)) Binomial[n, -k + n]. [From _Roger L. Bagula_, Feb 17 2009]

A051636.name: Number of "labeled" cyclic subgroups of alternating group A_n.
formula: a(n) = 1/2*Sum_{pi} (1+(-1)^(k_2+k_4+...)) * n!/(k_1!*1^k_1*k_2!*2^k_2*...*k_n!*n^k_n*phi(lcm{i:k_i != 0})), where pi runs through all partitions k_1+2*k_2+...+n*k_n=n and phi is Euler's function.

A051638.name: a(n) = sum_{k=0..n} (C(n,k) mod 3).
formula: Write n in base 3; if the representation contains r 1's and s 2's then a(n) = 2^{r-1} * (3^(s+1) - 1) = 1/2 * (3*A006047(n) - 2^(A062756(n))). - _Robin Chapman_, Ahmed Fares (ahmedfares(AT)my-deja.com) and others, Jul 16 2001

A051640.name: a(n) contains the digit b-1 in all bases b from 2 to n.

A051641.name: Palindromic binomial coefficients C(n,k) for k >= 2.

A051642.name: Values of A (the short leg) of a Pythagorean triangle with A and C (the hypotenuse) both prime and part of a twin prime.

A051643.name: Central elements in Parker's partition triangle.
formula: a(n) = coefficient of q^((m^2-1)/2) = q(2*n*(n+1)) in the q-binomial coefficient [2*m, m] = [2*(2*n+1), 2*n+1], where m = 2*n+1. [Corrected by _Petros Hadjicostas_, May 30 2020]
a(n) is the number of partitions of 2*n*(n+1) into at most 2*n+1 parts each no bigger than 2*n+1. - _Petros Hadjicostas_, May 30 2020

A051644.name: Primes of the form 6*p + 1 where p is also prime.

A051645.name: Primes p such that 30*p+1 is also prime.

A051646.name: Primes of the form 30*p + 1 where p is also prime.

A051647.name: Primes p such that 210*p + 1 is also prime.

A051648.name: Primes of form 210*p + 1 where p is a prime.

A051649.name: Primes of the form 2310*p + 1 where p is a prime.

A051650.name: Lonely numbers: distance to closest prime sets a new record.

A051651.name: Primes of the form 30030*p + 1 where p is a prime.

A051652.name: Smallest number at distance n from nearest prime.

A051653.name: Primes p such that 2310*p + 1 is also prime.

A051654.name: Primes p such that 30030*p + 1 is also prime.

A051655.name: Continued fraction for imaginary part of first zero (in critical strip) of Riemann zeta function.

A051656.name: Sum_{i=0..n} (C(n,i) mod 2)*Fibonacci(2*i).
formula: a(n) = sum_{i=0..n} (C(2n, 2i) mod 2)*F(2*i) = FL(n)product_{i=0..inf} L(2^i)^bit(n, i) where L is n-th Lucas number (A000032) and FL is defined as in A048757: FL(n) = n-th fibonacci number if n even, n-th Lucas number if n odd.

A051657.name: Experimental values for number of equal circles that are packed into a square for which the density of the packing is strictly increasing.

A051658.name: Experimental values for maximal number of contacts between equal circles and the box that are packed into a square.

A051659.name: Experimental values for maximal number of "loose" circles in packing equal circles into a square.

A051660.name: Experimental values for number of circles in packing equal circles into a square for which there is a loose circle.

A051661.name: Experimental values for number of circles in packing equal circles into a square for which there are no loose circles.

A051663.name: Primes p such that there is no Carmichael number pqr, p<q<r q, r primes.

A051664.name: a(n) is the number of nonzero coefficients in the n-th cyclotomic polynomial.

A051666.name: Rows of triangle formed using Pascal's rule except begin and end n-th row with n^2.

A051668.name: Rows of triangle formed using Pascal's rule except begin and end n-th row with (n+1)^2.

A051670.name: Smallest prime that concatenated with all previous terms of sequence forms a prime.

A051671.name: Smallest positive number whose digits concatenated with all previous terms forms a perfect square.

A051672.name: Triangle of up-down sums of k-th powers: a(n,k)=sum(i^k,i=1..n)+sum((n-i)^k,i=1..n-1), n,k>0.

A051673.name: Cubic star numbers: a(n) = n^3 + 4*Sum_{i=0..n-1} i^2.

A051676.name: Composite numbers n such that the number of divisors of n^2 is a prime.

A051679.name: Total number of even entries in first n rows of Pascal's triangle (the zeroth and first rows being 1; 1,1).

A051680.name: Number of n X n invertible matrices A over GF(3) such that A-I is invertible.
formula: a(n) = 3^binomial(n,2)*b(n), with b(0)=1, b(n)=(3^n-1)*b(n-1)+(-1)^(n). - _Vladeta Jovovic_, Aug 20 2006

A051681.name: Smallest term of first run of exactly n consecutive integers which are not squarefree.

A051682.name: 11-gonal (or hendecagonal) numbers: a(n) = n*(9*n-7)/2.
formula: Row sums of triangle A131432. - _Gary W. Adamson_, Jul 10 2007

A051683.name: Triangle read by rows: T(n,k) = n!*k.

A051684.name: Auxiliary sequence for calculation of number of even permutations of degree n and order exactly 2.

A051685.name: Auxiliary sequence for calculation of number of even permutations of degree n and order exactly 4.

A051686.name: Smallest prime p such that 2n*p+1 is also prime.

A051687.name: a(n) = (5*n+6)(!^5)/6, related to A008548 ((5*n+1)(!^5) quintic, or 5-factorials).

A051688.name: a(n) = (5*n+7)(!^5)/7(!^5), related to A034323 ((5*n+2)(!^5) quintic, or 5-factorials).

A051689.name: a(n) = (5*n+8)(!^5)/8(!^5), related to A034300 ((5*n+3)(!^5) quintic, or 5-factorials).

A051690.name: a(n) = (5*n+9)(!^5)/9(!^5), related to A034301 ((5*n+2)(!^5) quintic, or 5-factorials).

A051691.name: a(n) = (5*n+10)(!^5)/10(!^5), related to A052562 ((5*n)(!^5) quintic, or 5-factorials).

A051692.name: a(n) is twice the smallest k such that A051686(k) = prime(n).

A051693.name: Square array read by antidiagonals: a(n,k) = sum of two positive regular n-polytopic numbers (i.e., a(n,k) = binomial(x,n) + binomial(y,n) for some x,y >= n).

A051694.name: Smallest Fibonacci number that is divisible by n-th prime.
formula: log a(n) << (n log n)^2. - _Charles R Greathouse IV_, Jul 17 2012

A051695.name: Number of degree-n even permutations of order exactly 4.
formula: E.g.f.: (exp(x + x^2/2 + x^4/4) + exp(x - x^2/2 - x^4/4) - exp(x + x^2/2) - exp(x - x^2/2))/2. - _Andrew Howroyd_, Feb 01 2020

A051696.name: Greatest common divisor of n! and n^n.
formula: a(n) = Product_{p|n} p^(sum{k >= 1} floor(n/p^k)), where the product runs over the distinct primes p that divide n. - _Leroy Quet_, Apr 28 2007
a(n) = (numerator of B(n, 1/n))/n^(n - 1), where B(.,.) is the Euler beta function. - _Arkadiusz Wesolowski_, Nov 22 2017
a(p) = p for p prime. - _Peter Luschny_, Nov 29 2017

A051697.name: Closest prime to n (break ties by taking the smaller prime).

A051698.name: Closest prime to n that is different from n (break ties by taking the smaller prime).

A051699.name: Distance from n to closest prime.
formula: Conjecture: S(n) = sum(k=1, n, a(k) ) is asymptotic to C*n*log(n) with C=0.29...... - _Benoit Cloitre_, Aug 11 2002

Comment from _Giorgio Balzarotti_, Sep 18 2005: by means of the Prime Number Theorem is possible to derive the following inequality : c1*n*log(n) < S(n)< c2*n*log(n), where log is the natural logarithm and c1 = 1/4 and c2 = 3/8 (for n > 130). For a more accurate estimation of the values for c1 and c2, it necessary to know the number of twin primes with respect to the total number of primes.

A051700.name: Distance from n to closest prime that is different from n.

A051701.name: Closest prime to n-th prime p that is different from p (break ties by taking the smaller prime).

A051702.name: Distance from n-th prime to closest prime.

A051703.name: Maximal value of products of partitions of n into powers of distinct primes (1 not considered a power).

A051704.name: Maximal value of products of partitions of n into powers of distinct primes (powers of 1 and 2 excluded).

A051705.name: Numbers whose Japanese name lacks syllable "ku".

A051706.name: Number of different tennis scores after n points have been played.

A051707.name: Number of factorizations of (n,n) into pairs (j,k).

A051708.name: Number of ways to move a chess rook from the lower left corner to square (n,n), with the rook moving only up or right.
formula: G.f.: ((x*(1-x))/(sqrt(1-10*x+9*x^2)) + x)/2. - _Ralf Stephan_, Mar 23 2004; confirmed by Martin J. Erickson, Oct 05 2007
a(1)=1; a(2)=2; a(n) = ((10*n-16)*a(n-1) - (9*n-27)*a(n-2)) / (n-1), for n >= 3. - Martin J. Erickson (erickson(AT)truman.edu), Nov 12 2007
a(n) is asymptotic to (sqrt(2)/27)*9^n/(sqrt(Pi*n)). - Martin J. Erickson, Nov 09 2007
G.f.: A(x) satisfies 2 * x^3 = (1 - 9*x) * A(x) * (A(x) - x). - _Michael Somos_, Jan 08 2011
a(n) = Sum_{k=0..n} (k+1)*C(n-2,k-1)*hypergeom([2+k,2-n],[2],-1) for n >= 2. - _Peter Luschny_, Apr 20 2015

A051709.name: a(n) = sigma(n) + phi(n) - 2n.
formula: Dirichlet g.f.: zeta(s-1) * (zeta(s) - 2 + 1/zeta(s)). - _T. D. Noe_, Aug 01 2002
a(n) = A001065(n) - A051953(n).  [Difference between the sum of proper divisors of n and their Moebius-transform.]

This conjecture seems very easily provable to me: if the factorization of n is p1^k1 * p2^k2 * ... * pm^km, then the factorization of the largest squarefree divisor of n is p1 * p2 * ... * pm. So the factorization of A003557(n) is p1^(k1-1) * p2^(k2-1) * ... * pm^(km-1) if exponents of zero are allowed, or with the product terms that have an exponent of zero removed if they're not (if that results in an empty product, consider it to be 1 as usual).

The formula then follows from the fact that provided all ki >= 1, Max(k1, k2, ..., km) = Max(k1-1, k2-1, ..., km-1) + 1, and Max(k1-1, k2-1, ..., km-1) is not altered by removing the ki-1 values that are 0, provided we treat the empty Max() as being 0. That proves the formula and the provisos about empty products and Max() correspond to a(1) = 0.

Also, for any n, applying the formula Max(k1, k2, ..., km) times to n = p1^k1 * p2^k2 * ... * pm^km reduces all the exponents to zero, i.e., to the case a(1) = 0, so that case and the formula generate the sequence. (End)

A051913.name: Numbers n such that phi(n)/phi(phi(n)) = 3.
formula: Numbers n of the form 2^a*3^b*p*q*r*..., where p, q, r, ... are distinct primes of the form 2^x*3^y + 1 (i.e., belong to A005109) and phi(n) is not a power of 2 [Videla]. - _Robert G. Wilson v_, Apr 05 2005

A051914.name: Values of n at which record values in A052334 are reached.

A051915.name: Numbers k such that 2*k! + 1 is prime.

A051916.name: The Greek sequence: 2^a * 3^b * 5^c where a = 0,1,2,3,..., b,c in {0,1}, excluding the terms 1,2; that is: (a,b,c) != (0,0,0), (1,0,0).

A051917.name: Inverse of n under Nim (or Conway) multiplication.

A051918.name: Start with n, apply k->2k+1 until reach new record prime; sequence gives number of steps needed.

A051919.name: Start with n, apply k->2k+1 until reach new record prime; sequence gives record primes.

A051924.name: a(n) = binomial(2*n,n) - binomial(2*n-2,n-1); or (3n-2)*C(n-1), where C = Catalan numbers (A000108).
formula: G.f.: Sum_{n>=1} x^n/(1-x)^(2*n) * Sum_{k=0..n} C(n,k)^2 * x^k. - _Paul D. Hanna_, Nov 08 2014
a(n+1) = binomial(2*n, n)+2*sum(i=0, n-1, binomial(n+i, i) (V's in Pascal's Triangle). - _Jon Perry_ Apr 13 2004

a(n) = n*C(n-1) - (n-1)*C(n-2), where C(n) = A000108(n) = Catalan(n). For example, a(5) = 50 = 5*C(4) - 4*C(3) - 5*14 - 3*5 = 70 - 20. Triangle A128064 as an infinite lower triangular matrix * A000108 = A051924 prefaced with a 1: (1, 1, 4, 14, 50, 182, ...). - _Gary W. Adamson_, May 15 2009
Sum of 3 central terms of Pascal's triangle: 2*C(2+2*n, n)+C(2+2*n, 1+n). - _Zerinvary Lajos_, Dec 20 2005

The sequence 1,1,4,... has a(n)=C(2n,n)-C(2(n-1),n-1)=0^n+sum{k=0..n, C(n-1,k-1)*A002426(k)}, and g.f. given by (1-x)/(1-2x-2x^2/(1-2x-x^2/(1-2x-x^2/(1-2x-x^2/(1-.... (continued fraction). - _Paul Barry_, Oct 17 2009
D-finite with recurrence: a(n) = 2*(3*n-2)*(2*n-3)*a(n-1)/(n*(3*n-5)). - _Alois P. Heinz_, Apr 25 2014
a(n) = 2 * A097613(n) for n > 1. - _Bruce J. Nicholson_, Jan 06 2019

A051926.name: Number of independent sets of nodes in graph C_4 X P_n (n>2).

A051927.name: Number of independent vertex sets in the n-prism graph Y_n = K_2 X C_n (n > 2).
formula: Let A=[0, 1, 1;1, 1, 1;1, 1, 0] be the adjacency matrix of a triangle with a loop at a vertex. Then a(n)=trace(A^n). a(n)=(-1)^n+(1-sqrt(2))^n+(1+sqrt(2))^n. - _Paul Barry_, Jul 22 2004

A051928.name: Number of independent sets of vertices in graph K_3 X C_n (n > 2).

A051929.name: Number of independent sets of vertices in graph K_4 X C_n (n > 2).

A051930.name: Number of independent sets of vertices in graph K_5 X C_n (n > 2).

A051931.name: Number of independent sets of nodes in graph K_6 X C_n (n > 2).
formula: a(n) = (3 - sqrt(10))^n + (3 + sqrt(10))^n + 5 for n even.
a(n) = (3 - sqrt(10))^n + (3 + sqrt(10))^n - 5 for n odd.

A051932.name: Number of independent sets of nodes in graph K_7 X C_n (n > 2).

A051933.name: Triangle T(n,m) = Nim-sum (or XOR) of n and m, read by rows, 0<=m<=n.

A051934.name: a(n) = smallest palindrome > a(n-1) such that a(1)+a(2)+...+a(n) is a prime.

A051935.name: a(n) = smallest number > a(n-1) such that a(1) + a(2) + ... + a(n) is a prime.

A051936.name: Truncated triangular numbers: a(n) = n*(n+1)/2 - 9.
formula: a(n) = n + a(n-1) for n>4, a(4)=1. - _Vincenzo Librandi_, Aug 06 2010

A051937.name: Truncated triangular pyramid numbers: a(n) = Sum_{k=4..n} k*(k+1)/2-9.

A051938.name: Truncated triangular numbers: a(n) = n*(n+1)/2 - 18.
formula: a(n) = n + a(n-1) (with a(6)=3). - _Vincenzo Librandi_, Aug 06 2010

A051939.name: Truncated triangular pyramid numbers: a(n) = (n-5)*(n^2+8*n-66)/6.
formula: Equals binomial transform of (3, 10, 8, 1, 0, 0, 0, ...). - _Gary W. Adamson_, Jul 03 2008

A051940.name: Truncated triangular numbers: n*(n+1)/2 - 3*t*(t+1)/2 with t=4.
formula: a(n) = n + a(n-1) with n>8, a(8)=6. - _Vincenzo Librandi_, Aug 06 2010

A051941.name: Truncated triangular pyramid numbers: a(n) = (n-7)*(n^2 + 10*n - 108)/6, n >= 8.
formula: Binomial transform of [6, 15, 10, 1, 0, 0, 0, ...]. - _Gary W. Adamson_, Oct 22 2007

A051943.name: Truncated triangular pyramid numbers: a(n) = Sum_{k=9..n} (k*(k+1)/2 - 45).

A051944.name: a(n) = C(n)*(4n+1) where C(n) = Catalan numbers (A000108).
formula: The Hankel determinant transform is A025172(n-1). - _Michael Somos_, Sep 17 2006

A051945.name: a(n) = C(n)*(5n+1) where C(n) = Catalan numbers (A000108).

A051948.name: Numbers k such that k*sigma(k) == 2 (mod phi(k)).

A051950.name: Differences between values of tau(n) (A000005): a(n) = tau(n)-tau(n-1).

A051951.name: Second differences of tau(n).
formula: G.f.: -1/x + (1 - x)^2*Sum_{k>=1} x^(k-2)/(1 - x^k). - _Ilya Gutkovskiy_, Jan 29 2017

A051952.name: Numbers that are not a sum of 3 positive squares nor are of the form 4^a*(8b+7) and which are not multiples of 4.

A051953.name: Cototient(n) := n - phi(n).
formula: Equals Mobius transform (A054525) of A001065. - _Gary W. Adamson_, Jul 11 2008
Dirichlet convolution square of A317846/A046644 gives this sequence + A063524.

A051960.name: a(n) = C(n)*(3n+2) where C(n) = Catalan numbers = A000108.
formula: (n+1)*a(n) - 2*(n+2)*a(n-1) - 4*(2*n-3)*a(n-2) = 0. - conjectured by _R. J. Mathar_, Oct 02 2014, verified by _Robert Israel_, Sep 30 2015

formula: A050530(a(n)) = prime(n) and a(n) is the least number with this property.
